## CI/CD

Coming soon!‚Ñ¢Ô∏è
For now, you can integrate _places_ into your Python project or include it during CI build time. Simply run the required [`places generate environment`](#generate-environment) command manually to generate the `.env` file needed.

## FAQ

- **The hell is this? Do you have _any_ idea what you're doing?**  
    > No. Consider this a toy, a conversation starter. If this gains traction, those who truly know how things should be done will need to take over.  
    > This is my first public Python project/package, and it's full of firsts for me, so please keep that in mind. Also, I don't consider myself a professional programmer and have no formal education in this domain.

- **Why?**  
    > This started as a Hackathon project, and I felt the urge to complete and release something for once. Additionally, I'm preparing a tech stack I‚Äôd like to work with, and I wasn‚Äôt satisfied with the existing workflows for managing and syncing secrets (see below).

- **Is this for me/my project?**  
    > Again, consider this a toy. For now, use it only for private repositories and only with people you trust.

- **Is _places_ secure?**  
    > Debatable. In general, _places_ exposes encrypted data to others, meaning that with enough time and effort, it could be cracked. However, I‚Äôve tried to design _places_ to make this unlikely within reasonable boundaries. For instance:  
    > - [`places sync gitignore`](#sync-gitignore) is executed automatically, which should help prevent unencrypted data from being committed.  
    > - [`places generate key`](#generate-key) generates cryptographic keys with appropriate length and entropy.  
    > - `AES-512-GCM` with 210,000 iterations is used as per [OWASP recommendations](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html) (see [settings options](#settings) for more details).  
    >  
    > That said, I‚Äôve made some design decisions that may weaken security:  
    > - By default, a deterministic salt is used to allow for deterministic tracking of changes, which introduces some attack vectors. If security is critical, you can choose alternative salting strategies in [settings options](#settings).  
    > - The cryptographic key exchange between collaborators is manual, so it‚Äôs your responsibility to ensure it happens securely.  
    > - When using the shorthand to define a variable for multiple `.env` files, any encryption key can decrypt the encrypted value.  
    > - **If you identify any inherent security flaws in _places_, please let me know ASAP. Thank you!**

- **Instead of _places_ why not just use ‚Ä¶**
    - ‚Ä¶ [sops](https://github.com/getsops/sops)?
        > To be honest, I was overwhelmed at first glance and didn‚Äôt even try it. It‚Äôs almost certainly better and more secure in every regard than _places_, but at the same time, it looks cumbersome to set up.  
        > Additionally, I didn‚Äôt like how it seems to require (or strongly encourage) the use of another (potentially overkill) service for key management. Also, it appears to focus on file-based encryption rather than allowing for easy value-based encryption.
    - ‚Ä¶ [dotenv-vault](https://github.com/dotenv-org/dotenv-vault)?
        > Similar to [sops](https://github.com/getsops/sops), it looks great and might be a better solution for your use case. It‚Äôs also the closest alternative to _places_, so you may want to check it out.
        > What I prefer about _places_ is that it doesn't you you into the [dotenv.org](https://www.dotenv.org/)-ecosystem, that is that multiple `.env` files are derived from a single source of truth ([`places.yaml`](#placesyaml)). Additionally, [`places watch start`](#watch-start) persistently tracks changes in [`places.yaml`](#placesyaml) and automatically manages [encryption](#encrypt), [decryption](#decrypt), and [`auto-updates`](#generate-environment) for your `.env` files.
    - ‚Ä¶ [Infisical](https://infisical.com/)?
      > I genuinely wanted to like it, but their documentation is currently a mess. It took me over half an hour to locate their current Python library, which wasn‚Äôt even referenced in the documentation. I ultimately gave up, frustrated, when attempting to align secrets with my version tags.
    - ‚Ä¶ [HashiCorp Vault](https://www.hashicorp.com/products/vault)?
        > Yeah, [no](https://www.hashicorp.com/products/vault/pricing).
    - ‚Ä¶ git hooks?
        > Glad you asked! This project actually started as Git hooks, and you can find a very basic MVP in [places-mini](places-mini). It uses a single key to encrypt local `.env` files but lacks many of the convenient features of _places_. For example, you‚Äôll need to manually ensure that all the appropriate entries are added to `.gitignore`, among other things. Also, it uses a naughty hack to track changes and force encryption. Don't use it.

- **Why is the code so bad?**
    > As I mentioned earlier, I‚Äôm neither a professional coder nor experienced with the Python ecosystem. Additionally, I‚Äôve made some questionable decisions along the way.
  
- **Why didn't you just use [ruamel.yaml](https://sourceforge.net/projects/ruamel-yaml/)?**
    > I probably should have, as it would have saved me a lot of trouble. However, I couldn‚Äôt get it to work the way I wanted. Even when configured for `round_trip`, _ruamel.yaml_ would mess with comments, whitespace, etc. I want [`places.yaml`](#placesyaml) to remain virtually unchanged after a [`places encrypt`](#encrypt) ‚ôªÔ∏è [`places decrypt`](#decrypt) roundtrip. That said, it is possible I just did not configure it correctly.

- **Why can‚Äôt the generated `.env` files be styled, structured, or annotated?**
  > It's on the [roadmap](#roadmap) below.

## Roadmap

* **CI/CD:** Provide a convient Github Action and Gitlab [CI/CD](#cicd) integration for _places_.
* **Comments in `.env` files**: Add `comment`property to variables
* **Layouting in `.env` files**: Add "meta-variables" (eg. `places.section`) that add sections and linebreaks at gen-time.

## Known issues / Limitations
* _places_ does not adhere to the [YAML specifications](https://yaml.org/)
* Only array/lists in square brackets are supported.
* Comments get eaten when placed after `|-`

***

# places CLI Documentation

## add environment

Add a new environment configuration.

```shell
places add environment NAME [OPTIONS]
```

<details>

***

<summary>Options & Arguments</summary>


**Options**

| Short | Long Option | Description |
|-------|-------------|-------------|
| `-f` | `--filepath <filepath>` | Path to environment file. |
| `-w` | `--watch <watch>` | Enable file watching. |
| `-a` | `--alias <alias>` | Environment aliases. |
| `-k` | `--key <key>` | Key to use for encryption. |


**Arguments**

| Argument | Required |
|----------|----------|
| `NAME` | ‚ùå |

***

</details>

## add key

Add an existing key file reference to places.yaml

```shell
places add key NAME [OPTIONS]
```

<details>

***

<summary>Options & Arguments</summary>


**Options**

| Short | Long Option | Description |
|-------|-------------|-------------|
| `-a` | `--add` | Add key reference to places.yaml |


**Arguments**

| Argument | Required |
|----------|----------|
| `NAME` | ‚ùå |

***

</details>

## add key_from_string

Add a key from a provided string with the specified name.

```shell
places add key_from_string NAME KEY_STRING [OPTIONS]
```

<details>

***

<summary>Options & Arguments</summary>


**Options**

| Short | Long Option | Description |
|-------|-------------|-------------|
| `-a` | `--add` | Add key to places.yaml |
| `-f` | `--force-overwrite` | Force overwrite without safety checks. |


**Arguments**

| Argument | Required |
|----------|----------|
| `NAME` | ‚ùå |
| `KEY_STRING` | ‚ùå |

***

</details>

## add setting

Add or update settings configuration.

```shell
places add setting [OPTIONS]
```

<details>

***

<summary>Options</summary>


**Options**

| Short | Long Option | Description |
|-------|-------------|-------------|
| `-sg` | `--sync-gitignore <sync_gitignore>` | Enable/disable .gitignore sync. |
| `-i` | `--iterations <iterations>` | Number of iterations for cryptography. |
| `-hf` | `--hash-function <hash_function>` | Hash function for cryptography. |
| `-sm` | `--salt-mode <salt_mode>` | Salt mode for cryptography. |
| `-sf` | `--salt-filepath <salt_filepath>` | Salt filepath for cryptography. |
| `-sv` | `--salt-value <salt_value>` | Salt value for cryptography. |

***

</details>

## add variable

Add a new variable configuration.

```shell
places add variable NAME [OPTIONS]
```

<details>

***

<summary>Options & Arguments</summary>


**Options**

| Short | Long Option | Description |
|-------|-------------|-------------|
| `-v` | `--value <value>` | Value of variable / secret. |
| `-k` | `--key <key>` | Key to use for encryption. |
| `-u` | `--unencrypt <unencrypt>` | Mark value as unencrypted. |
| `-e` | `--environment <environment>` | Target environment(s). |


**Arguments**

| Argument | Required |
|----------|----------|
| `NAME` | ‚ùå |

***

</details>

## decrypt

Decrypt `.places/places.enc.yaml` into `places.yaml` file.

```shell
places decrypt [OPTIONS]
```

## encrypt

Encrypt `places.yaml` into `.places/places.enc.yaml` file.

```shell
places encrypt [OPTIONS]
```

## generate environment

Generate .env files for specified environments or all environments defined in `places.yaml`

This generally follows [https://dotenv-linter.github.io/](https://dotenv-linter.github.io/) rules, with the exception of alphabetical ordering.

```shell
places generate environment [ENVIRONMENT]... [OPTIONS]
```

<details>

***

<summary>Options & Arguments</summary>


**Options**

| Short | Long Option | Description |
|-------|-------------|-------------|
| `-a` | `--all` | Generate .env files for all environments. |


**Arguments**

| Argument | Required |
|----------|----------|
| `ENVIRONMENT` | ‚ùå |

***

</details>

## generate key

Generate a new encryption key with the specified name.

```shell
places generate key [NAME] [OPTIONS]
```

<details>

***

<summary>Options & Arguments</summary>


**Options**

| Short | Long Option | Description |
|-------|-------------|-------------|
| `-l` | `--length <length>` | Custom length for generated key in bytes. |
| `-a` | `--add` | Add key to places.yaml |


**Arguments**

| Argument | Required |
|----------|----------|
| `NAME` | ‚ùå |

***

</details>

## init

Initialize a new places project.

Also generates a new default encryption key and adds it to `.places/keys/`.

```shell
places init [OPTIONS]
```

<details>

***

<summary>Options</summary>


**Options**

| Short | Long Option | Description |
|-------|-------------|-------------|
| `-t` | `--template <template>` | Template to use for initialization |
| `--list-templates` | `--list-templates` | List available templates |

***

</details>

## run test

Run tests.

Currently supported tests: e2e, cli.

Specify test names or use ‚Äìall flag.

```shell
places run test [TESTS]... [OPTIONS]
```

<details>

***

<summary>Options & Arguments</summary>


**Options**

| Short | Long Option | Description |
|-------|-------------|-------------|
| `-a` | `--all` | Run all tests. |


**Arguments**

| Argument | Required |
|----------|----------|
| `TESTS` | ‚ùå |

***

</details>

## sync gitignore

Sync .gitignore with Places entries.

```shell
places sync gitignore [OPTIONS]
```

## watch start

Start watching for changes.

```shell
places watch start [OPTIONS]
```

<details>

***

<summary>Options</summary>


**Options**

| Short | Long Option | Description |
|-------|-------------|-------------|
| `-s` | `--service` | Run watcher as a persistent system service. |
| `-d` | `--daemon` | Run watcher as a background daemon. |

***

</details>

## watch stop

Stop watching for changes.

```shell
places watch stop [OPTIONS]
```

<details>

***

<summary>Options</summary>


**Options**

| Short | Long Option | Description |
|-------|-------------|-------------|
| `-s` | `--service` | Stop and remove persistent system service. |
| `-d` | `--daemon` | Stop daemon process. |

***

</details>
